defaultWritten evidence submitted by defaultthe Medical Schools Council and Dental Schools (WSC064)default&#xa0;default1.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBoth organisations represent the interests and ambitions of UK medical and dental schools as they relate to the generation of national health, wealth and knowledge through biomedical research and the professions of medicine and dentistry. 
default&#xa0;default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis submission
default includes contributions received from individual responses, UK medical and dental schools and the Equality Challenge Unit, Athena SWAN Medical and Dental Schools Advisory Group.
default&#xa0;default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDifficulties related to working in STEM 
defaultclinical and non-cl
defaultinical 
defaultacademic careers are faced by both men and women. However, 
defaultwider
default issues affect the 
defaultretention and progression of women
default in academic STEM careers
default for example, limited 
defaultsenior women role models
default, women often having a greater proportion of teaching/pastor
defaultal student roles, limited opportunities for part-time/flexible working, 
defaultand 
defaultwomen taking on the major
defaultity of caring responsibilities. T
defaulthe cycle is self-perpetuating. 
default&#xa0;default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a 
defaultgendered conception of merit in clinical and non-clinical academia
default, especially
default one tha
defaultt values a full-time/long-hours
default uninterrupted career trajectory and research success. The achievements that women make are often unrecognised, as women are often too modest and do not market themselves enough, or reaching the same level of achievement either takes longer, or does not oc
defaultcur to the same level, due to career breaks, work-life balance and return to work challenges.
default defaultWomen Professors have increased by only 5% since 2004 (from 11% to 16%
default1
default), and more work is required to ensure gender balance at senior academic levels.
default&#xa0;default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe drain
default of women from academic medicine and dentistry represents a significant 
defaultloss of talent and expertise to the HE and research sectors
default, to the detriment of research innovation and leadership. There is some evidence that the number and proportion of wome
defaultn in s
defaultenior roles is increasing
default – however, this is o
defaultc
defaultcurring very slowly and needs urgent attention.
default&#xa0;default2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMedical and dental school initiatives to support academic women are commended and should be sustained and expanded. Such initiatives support the goals and ambit
defaultions of the Athena SWAN charter for Women in Science, which UK medical and dental schools are working towards and several have achieved Silver or Bronze awards.
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultStructured clinical academic training pathways e.g. NIHR should be protected and marketed as a
defaultspirational.
default&#xa0;
default2.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a need to provide affordable, quality childcare. 
